    <h1>
     [FR]: Keep Cool, Stay Safe!
    </h1>
    <p class="lede">
     <strong>
      [FR]: Extreme Heat Emergency Safety Guide — Save and Share This Page
     </strong>
    </p>
    <div class="actions no-print">
     <a class="btn" href="javascript:window.print()">
      [FR]: Print this flyer
     </a>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: 🕒 3 Golden Rules of Heat Safety
    </h2>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      1. Hydrate, Hydrate, Hydrate 💧
     </span>
     <ul>
      <li>
       [FR]: Drink water
       <strong>
        [FR]: even if you do not feel thirsty
       </strong>
       [FR]: . Drink regularly and take extra water in heavy heat or sweating; if a doctor limits your fluids, ask what is safe for you.
      </li>
      <li>
       [FR]: Avoid alcohol; do not rely mainly on very sugary drinks. Caffeine affects people differently—choose water or electrolytes if you feel unwell or are sweating heavily.
      </li>
      <li>
       [FR]: If you are sweating heavily for a long time, replace salts too: use ORS/electrolytes, a sports drink, or food with salt plus water if appropriate.
      </li>
     </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      2. Keep Your Environment Cool 🏠
     </span>
     <ul>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Create Cross-Ventilation:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Keep windows and blinds closed when outdoor air is hotter than indoor air; open them when outdoor air becomes cooler and safe.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: The Wet Sheet Trick:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Damp skin or cloths and use a fan for evaporative cooling if safe; keep electrical devices away from water and cords out of walkways.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Foot Baths &amp; Sprays:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Soak your feet in cool water or use a spray bottle to damp your skin. Evaporating water can help cool the body.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Limit Appliance Use:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Avoid using ovens, stoves, or dryers, as they emit immense heat into your home.
      </li>
     </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      3. Check In on Others 🤝
     </span>
     <ul>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Buddy Up:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Call or visit older adults, people living alone, unhoused neighbors, outdoor workers, and people with health conditions at least daily during severe heat if safe and welcomed.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [FR]: Never Leave Anyone in Cars:
       </strong>
       [FR]: Never leave children, pets, or vulnerable individuals in a parked car, even with windows cracked. Temperatures inside cars can spike to lethal levels in minutes.
      </li>
     </ul>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: ⚕️ Know the Warning Signs
    </h2>
    <div class="two">
     <div class="box warn">
      <span class="tag warn">
       Heat Exhaustion — Act Quick!
      </span>
      <h3>
       [FR]: What you see:
      </h3>
      <ul>
       <li>
        [FR]: Cool, pale, clammy skin
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Heavy sweating
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Fast, weak pulse
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Muscle cramps, headache, nausea, weakness, dizziness
       </li>
      </ul>
      <h3>
       [FR]: What to do:
      </h3>
      <p>
       [FR]: Move to a cool place. Loosen clothing. Sip water slowly. Put cool, wet cloths on your skin or take a cool bath. Get medical help if symptoms worsen or last longer than 1 hour.
      </p>
     </div>
     <div class="box emergency">
      <span class="tag">
       Heat Stroke — Call emergency services
      </span>
      <h3>
       [FR]: What you see:
      </h3>
      <ul>
       <li>
        <strong>
         [FR]: Very high body temperature
        </strong>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: (if you can measure it, 103°F / 39.4°C or higher)
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Hot, red skin (dry or damp)
       </li>
       <li>
        [FR]: Fast, strong pulse
       </li>
       <li>
        <strong>
         [FR]: Confusion
        </strong>
        [FR]: , slurred speech, vomiting, loss of consciousness
       </li>
      </ul>
      <h3>
       [FR]: What to do:
      </h3>
      <p>
       <strong>
        [FR]: CALL YOUR LOCAL EMERGENCY NUMBER IMMEDIATELY.
       </strong>
       [FR]: Move the person to a cool area. Do NOT give anything to drink if they are confused, unconscious, vomiting repeatedly, or unable to swallow safely. Cool them down immediately with wet cloths, ice packs, or a cool bath until help arrives.
      </p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [FR]: 📞 Local Emergency Resources
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Emergency Services:
      </strong>
      [FR]: Call
      <strong>
       [FR]: your local emergency number
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: (911 in the U.S./Canada; verify locally) for life-threatening situations.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Non-Emergency Services &amp; Info:
      </strong>
      [FR]: Where available, call
      <strong>
       211
      </strong>
      ,
      <strong>
       311
      </strong>
      [FR]: , or your local health/emergency-management office to find cooling centers, water distribution points, and energy assistance programs.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      Local Contacts (Fill in)
     </span>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Nearest Cooling Center:
      </strong>
      [FR]: __________________________________________________
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [FR]: Local Mutual-Aid Contact:
      </strong>
      [FR]: __________________________________________________
     </p>
    </div>
    <p class="sources">
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [FR]: Sources: CDC Heat &amp; Health guidelines, NWS Safety Tips, WHO fact sheets. General information only. Public domain (CC0 1.0).
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     [FR]: This guide is general information, not medical advice, and is not a substitute for professional emergency care or training. In an emergency, always call your local emergency number. When symptoms are severe or you are unsure, treat it as an emergency. Reuse and reprint freely.
    </p>
